{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8dbcff2d-c63c-4c27-ba3d-aaaf7278012b","content":"On macOS, when a process crashes the system automatically generates a **crash report**. You can find it in:\n\n1. **User-level reports:**\n   `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\n2. **System-level reports:**\n   `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`\n\nLook for files named like `YourAppName_<date>_<host>.ips` (or `.crash` on older macOS versions).\n\nYou can also open **Console.app** → sidebar → **Crash Reports** to browse them with a GUI.\n\n### Core dumps\n\nIf you need a full core dump (not just the Apple crash report), enable them:\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\n\nThen run your app — the core file will typically be written to `/cores/core.<pid>`.\n\n> **Note:** On Apple Silicon, SIP may prevent core dumps for some processes. You may need to disable SIP or use `lldb` to attach and capture state instead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c2a0218a-0b19-4aef-92a3-6a0e0fe01f75","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":297,"requestId":"1BC2:1B7339:15D3CB0:18860AF:6A0286E1"},"id":"fa9ed3a5-aba4-4c8d-a8eb-7d73fd437384","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:48:28.172Z","parentId":"c6a64cb5-c52d-480d-b92b-0a52e6c564b2"}
